12.06.2006 

School of the future - German, French and Croatian under a roof
Dozens of successful ?overseas? German schools operate around the world, but the latest addition to the family in Zagreb, is unique.

The German International School in the Croatian capital Zagreb is a so-called Euro-campus, meaning that a German and a French school are working under the same roof. Some classes are taught separated, but others jointly.

English is the mandatory language and Croatian is taught too. ?We want to put programmes together, in a globally brand new concept,? says principal, Sigrid Pohler. With a German colleague, four German-speaking local staffers and two kindergarten teachers she runs the German side of the experimental curriculum.

The project was launched last year and 35 children now go to class, says the head of the school union, Bruno Boban. Roughly 40 per cent of the students are Croats and the majority is made up of those from German or Austrian families. In the mid-term, children from the alumni are expected to become ?multipliers of German-Croatian relations.?

?At first it is not easy for a child to find itself in front of a teacher who doesn't speak its language,? Pohler explains. Physical education is conducted in German, music in French and art in Croatian. ?It is a huge opportunity for these children and they quickly accepted it as being thoroughly normal,? says Sanja Jelicic, the parents' representative. She appreciates the intimacy of the tiny school, which now has the first four grades. ?It also brings the parents closer together and they become engaged in activities other than the programme,? she says. When the school building, a rented former Jesuit seminary, needed painting last September, the parents and teachers happily grabbed buckets and brushes. ?And we finished in time.?

German and French students are kept apart in grades one and two and are together in the next two. The goal is to add another grade year-on-year and keep the students going until they graduate with German or French diplomas after 25 years of studying. Their education will also be recognized by Croatian authorities. Financial support proves that the opportunities of the concept were immediately recognized. The German province Baden-Wuerttemberg, the programme of which is taught in the Zagreb school, is among the donors, along with Croat and German sponsors from the business community supporting what they agree is a ?concept of the future.?

Source: syl.0b20n1n312719.org

