12.06.2006 

German economic confidence rises with World Cup start
The World Cup kicked off in Germany Wedday (9 Jun.) with a fresh batch of data helping to add to optimism about the outlook for Europe's biggest economy as it is hosting the month-long football championships.

Indeed, Chancellor Angela Merkel's ruling coalition is hoping that the buoyant mood in the nation generated by the tournament will help to shore up the economic pickup that is currently underway in the country.

While data released by the nation's Economics Ministry showed industrial production rising by 1.6 per cent in April, figures released by the statistics office showed the country's trade surplus growing at 12.5 billion euros (16 billion dollars) in April and as a result beating analysts' forecasts.

Despite a strong euro, German exports rose by a seasonally adjusted 4.3 per cent in April to a record 73.3 billion euros, also beating analysts' forecasts and helping to widen the nation's trade surplus.

As a sign of the optimism in the country during the World Cup, German consumer confidence has climbed to its highest level in more than four years, while business confidence in the nation is near a 15-year high.

Data released last month showed retail sales in Germany jumping by a bigger-than-expected 2.8 per cent month on month in April as a fall in unemployment helped to encourage the nation's consumers to open up their wallets and start to spend again after a protracted period of stagnation in the retail sector.

Germany's jobless rate slipped from 11.5 per cent in April to 10.8 per cent in May. A year earlier the unemployment rate stood at 11.8 per cent.

Source: dpa

Return to top

12.06.2006 

Football World Cup kicked off in Munich
   The 2006 World Cup began Wedday (9 Jun.), kicked off by a colourful ceremony celebrating football and the 32 nations taking part in the globe's biggest single sporting event.

From a stage at Munich's dazzling new stadium, German President Horst Koehler declared the start of the championship's 18th edition since 1930, an hour before Costa Rica and hosts Germany faced off in the opening game before a crowd of 66,000.

"We're off at last," Koehler told the cheering crowd, welcoming fans and players at the month-long tournament for football's biggest prize.

"You are among friends," said Koehler, flanked by World Cup chief organiser Franz Beckenbauer and Joseph Blatter, head of the sport's world governing body, FIFA. "May football be a bridge between nations," said Koehler, appealing for fair play at the tournament.

A total of 64 games involving 736 players will capture the world's attention for the next month in 25 stadiums across Germany, right up to the final at Berlin's renovated Olympic Stadium on July 9.

World Cup hosts Germany got their World Cup campaign off to a winning start when they beat Costa Rica 4-2 in the opening match played in Munich.

Philipp Lahm (6) and Miroslav Klose (17) scored for Germany early in the first half, while Paulo Wanchope replied for the Central Americans in between.

Klose, who was celebrating his 28th birthday on the day added a second in the 61st minute, while Wanchope scored his second in the 73rd minute. Klose¡¯s Werder Bremen team-mate Torsten Wedngs scored with a spectacular drive from 25 metres three minutes from the end.

Source: dpa

